{"descriptions":[{"id":1419,"title":null,"content":"\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003eThere are major divergences between the literary and spoken registers in this domain. In either case, relative clauses are formed with the use of nominalizers, but the markers for nominalizing verbs have different forms and functions (for oral Tibetan, see xxlink MST 26).\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003eThe universal marker of nominalization in Tibetan is \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eཔ་\u003c/span\u003e / \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eབ་\u003c/span\u003e. However, the following markers are also found: \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eབྱེད་\u003c/span\u003e, \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eབྱ་\u003c/span\u003e, \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eརྒྱུ་\u003c/span\u003e, \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eཡུལ་\u003c/span\u003e, \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eས་\u003c/span\u003e, \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eམཁན་\u003c/span\u003e, \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eམི་\u003c/span\u003e. Apart from these common nominalizers, there are also markers that convey a complete meaning: \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eསྲོལ་\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;custom, usage,\u0026rdquo; \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eསྟངས་\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;way, manner,\u0026rdquo; \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eའཕྲོ་\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;sequel, continuation\u0026rdquo; and \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eའོ་ཅོག་\u003c/span\u003e, \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eདགུ་\u003c/span\u003e, \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eཚད་\u003c/span\u003e which mean \u0026ldquo;all, altogether.\u0026rdquo;\u003ca href=\"#_ftn1\"\u003e[1]\u003c/a\u003e The markers \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eཅན་\u003c/span\u003e and \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eལྡན་\u003c/span\u003e are also used to form relative clauses, but they differ from the others insofar as they function, by themselves, as nominalized possessive verbs.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003eAs in the case of their oral homologues, all the nominalizers with the exception of \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eཔ་\u003c/span\u003e depend on the function of the head noun (antecedent) and, in certain cases, on the tense of the relative clause. Relative clauses usually go before the head noun, but occasionally appear after. In the former case, they are usually (though not always) linked to the noun that they modify by means of a genitive. Finally, in Classical Tibetan, we sometimes find (associated with the nominalizer) a true relative pronoun: \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eགང་\u003c/span\u003e (see the example with \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eཔ་\u003c/span\u003e). The following table summarizes the uses of the most common forms.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ctable border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"146\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eNominalizing\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"146\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSuffix Function of the Head Noun\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"146\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eVerb Form\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"146\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePossible Translations\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"146\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eཔ་\u003c/span\u003e / \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eབ་\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"146\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003eSubject, Object, etc. (by default)\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"146\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003eCompatible with all tenses\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"146\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003e\u0026ldquo;Who,\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;What,\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;To whom,\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;Where,\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;Whose,\u0026rdquo; etc.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"146\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eབྱེད་\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"146\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003eInstrument, Cause, or Manner\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"146\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003ePresent\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"146\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003e\u0026ldquo;With which,\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;Which\u0026rdquo;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"146\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eརྒྱུ་\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"146\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003eObject\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003eSubject (intransitive)\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"146\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003eFuture\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"146\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003e\u0026ldquo;That\u0026rdquo;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"146\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eབྱ་\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"146\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003eObject\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003eSubject (intransitive)\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"146\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003eFuture\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"146\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003e\u0026ldquo;That\u0026rdquo;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"146\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eཡུལ་\u003c/span\u003e / \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eས་\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"146\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003eIndirect Object or Place Adverbial\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"146\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003eFuture or Present\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"146\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003e\u0026ldquo;Where,\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;To whom,\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;To which,\u0026rdquo; etc.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"146\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eམཁན་\u003c/span\u003e / \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eམི་\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"146\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003eSubject\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"146\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003ePresent\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"146\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003e\u0026ldquo;Who\u0026rdquo;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\n\u003c/table\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003eThe nominalizers are briefly described and illustrated in the following sections.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003chr size=\"1\" /\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ca href=\"#_ftnref1\"\u003e[1]\u003c/a\u003e These three nominalizers have been described in Stephan Beyer, \u003cem\u003eThe Classical Tibetan Language\u003c/em\u003e (Albany: State University of New York Press, 1992).\u003c/p\u003e","source_url":null,"is_primary":true,"created_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:52 UTC","updated_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:52 UTC","authors":[{"id":"6","fullname":"Nicolas Tournadre"}]}]}